Hook Chain Fragility

TW's `$tw.hooks.invokeHook` passes each hook's return value as input to the next hook. There is NO try/catch. If any hook returns `undefined` (forgetting `return tiddler`), all subsequent hooks silently receive `undefined` and fail.

```javascript
// BROKEN — breaks the chain for all hooks registered after this one
$tw.hooks.addHook("th-deleting-tiddler", function(tiddler) {
    doSomething(tiddler);
    // Missing: return tiddler;
});

// CORRECT
$tw.hooks.addHook("th-deleting-tiddler", function(tiddler) {
    doSomething(tiddler);
    return tiddler;
});
```

Known offender: `sq/streams` plugin's `th-deleting-tiddler` hook.

You cannot control hook registration order reliably (depends on startup module load order). So never rely solely on a hook for critical operations.

Robust pattern — two-layer approach:

1. **Hook** (best-effort): show confirm dialogs, record user decisions
2. **Change event** (reliable fallback): `$tw.wiki.addEventListener("change", ...)` fires after every wiki store change, regardless of hooks

```javascript
// Snapshot approach: track state BEFORE deletion
var snapshot = {};  // title → {data}

// Keep snapshot updated via change event
$tw.wiki.addEventListener("change", function(changes) {
    $tw.utils.each(changes, function(change, title) {
        if(!change.deleted) {
            // Update snapshot for modified/added tiddlers
        } else {
            // Tiddler deleted — use snapshot to act
            var info = snapshot[title];
            delete snapshot[title];
            if(info) { /* cleanup */ }
        }
    });
});
```

Draft safety: when a user opens an editor and cancels, the draft tiddler (which inherits fields like `_canonical_uri` from the original) gets deleted. Always check for `draft.of` field:

```javascript
// In snapshot building — skip drafts
var titles = $tw.wiki.filterTiddlers("[has[_canonical_uri]!has[draft.of]]");

// In change event — skip drafts
if(t && t.fields["draft.of"]) return;
```
